+	// byte-identical to UDS. On any ring miss, fall back to the UDS wrapper. Folded away (always
+	// returns -1) unless built with -DDARLING_RING_TRANSPORT.
+	if (__dserver_ring_mach_port_mod_refs(target, name, right, delta, &code) != 0) {
+		code = dserver_rpc_mach_port_mod_refs(target, name, right, delta);
+	}
 
 	if (code < 0) {
 		__simple_printf("mach_port_deallocate failed (internally): %d\n", code);

From cd9e7cc704f52385e0cd0e5dfe14bf2e3121f51e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 13:12:20 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P5-bulk (dar-1il.1): guest ring path for
 mach_port_allocate + insert_right

Adds guest ring helpers __dserver_ring_mach_port_allocate / _insert_right (both via
the existing gr_body_trap: inline body in, header-only kern_return_t reply out) and
routes the _kernelrpc_*_trap_impl wrappers ring-first / UDS-fallback. allocate sends
its out-`name` as the guest VA (uint64_t); the server writes the allocated name into
guest memory via the generic Call path exactly as over UDS.

mach_port_deallocate is REVERTED to UDS-only: under launchd's real workload it
destroys ports backing mapped regions -> vm munmap S2C upcall to the calling thread,
which a ring-waiting (non-recvmsg) thread cannot service -> deadlock. (Helper kept in
dserver-ring.c but no longer routed; see the membership rule in
DSERVER_RING_C2S_OPCODES, darlingserver rpc-supplement.h.)

OFF-build is byte-identical (everything gated behind DARLING_RING_TRANSPORT; OFF
stubs return -1). Validated: 14-edge byte-identical kern_return ring-vs-true-UDS;
allocate ~5.1x / insert_right ~6.4x over UDS p50; boot + fork-storm 3/3 clean.
