From dfcbe9923500d879e9cc4c1fb05d18e9ec77488d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 05:19:39 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P8 D4 (dar-1il.3.2.1): guest -- mach_port_deallocate
 via the duplex lane + munmap pump

Guest side of the deallocate-via-duplex migration (server side: darlingserver @297143f).

dserver-ring.c: gr_duplex_pump_once now handles the REAL munmap S2C upcall shape
(DSERVER_RING_DUPLEX_UPCALL_MUNMAP) -- it runs the SAME munmap(2) the UDS recvmsg S2C path runs, ON
THE CALLER thread, and publishes the kernel return_value + errno via publish_munmap_reply, so the
side effect is byte-identical to UDS (only the transport differs).
__dserver_ring_mach_port_deallocate_duplex publishes the deallocate as a duplex parent request and
waits via gr_duplex_wait_reply (the bounded, S2C-pumping wait), advertising DUPLEX_CAP_DEALLOCATE.
On a DSERVER_RING_DUPLEX_DECLINE reply or any transport miss it returns -1 -> the trap impl
UDS-falls-back (safe: the server declines pre-mutation, so no double-effect). Routed ONLY behind the
per-command hatch DARLING_GUEST_DUPLEX_DEALLOCATE=1 (default OFF, same warm-server discipline as the
D3 selftest) -- gr_dealloc_via_duplex_enabled scans /proc/self/environ libc-free.

mach_traps.c: _kernelrpc_mach_port_deallocate_trap_impl tries the duplex lane first (folds away
unless -DDARLING_RING_TRANSPORT; a strict no-op unless the hatch is set), then UDS.

Live A/B (warm boot): deallocate rides the duplex lane (server ring_duplex_parent=11), side effects
byte-identical to UDS, no wedge, fork-storm 3/3, isolation holds. mach_port_deallocate does not
drive a munmap S2C in Darling (mach_make_memory_entry_64 stubbed), so the deadlock-cure case is N/A
for this op; default-OFF. See the server commit for the full disposition.
---
