From bd10efc5418e61c00753ea9de3285b1e54b7bd46 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 11:08:26 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P8 D11 (dar-1il.6): migrate uidgid +
 set_thread_handles + started_suspended + get_tracer + task_is_64_bit as
 Tier-1 generic-fiber ring ops (guest)

Guest side of the D11 bulk closed-fast Lane-1 batch (server side in the matching
darlingserver commit). Adds gr_full_trap() -- a generalization of gr_body_trap that
ALSO copies out a FIXED reply body (not just the kern_return code), validating the
reply is exactly {reply_hdr, replylen-byte body} so a wrong-shape reply is treated as a
transport miss -> UDS-fall-back. Five per-op wrappers (__dserver_ring_uidgid /
set_thread_handles / started_suspended / get_tracer / task_is_64_bit) mirror the matching
dserver_rpc_<op> contract: 0 + out-params written on a valid ring round-trip, negative on
any transport miss. The request/reply body layouts are byte-identical to the generated
dserver_call_<op>_t / dserver_reply_<op>_t structs (verified against the build's rpc.h),
so the server rebuilds {callhdr, body} and dispatches via the SAME dtape primitive as UDS.
Folded-away stubs keep a non-ring build byte-identical.

Wired the 6 BSD call sites to try-ring-then-UDS (getuid.c uidgid x2, sigexc.c
started_suspended + get_tracer, bsdthread_register.c set_thread_handles x2,
sysctl_proc.c/sysctl_sysctl.c/proc_info.c task_is_64_bit), preserving each site's exact
result semantics (e.g. sysctl_sysctl returns -ENOENT on failure; the others set a default).
These are NOT no-fiber ops (Tier-1 generic fiber); no change to ringFastPathEligible.

Live A/B proved byte-identical state ring-vs-UDS and fork-storm 3/3 clean -- see the
darlingserver commit for the full measurement. Routes over the ring iff each op is in
DSERVER_RING_C2S_OPCODES; on any miss the caller UDS-falls-back.
